I already tried stackoverflow for this und you might want to check out my description there (also a jsfiddle in the comments).

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29678494/nested-children-nodes-in-navigation-tree-inherit-link-tag-from-their-parent-node

I'm trying to create a nested navigation tree of unordered lists with list items containing &lt;a&gt; tags. The sublevel lists gain an unintentional &lt;a&gt; tag with link but without description. It can be discovered in the html source and also be styled via CSS. If I substitute the &lt;a&gt; tag for e.g. a &lt;div&gt; the behaviour disappears.

```
let NodeTree = React.createClass({
  render: function () {
    return (
      <ul>
        {this.props.tree.map(function (node) {
          return <NodeTree.Item key={node.id} data={node}/>
        })}
      </ul>
    );
  }
});

NodeTree.Item = React.createClass({
  render: function () {
    return (
      <li>
        <NodeTree.Content data={this.props.data}/>
      </li>
    );
  }
});

NodeTree.Content = React.createClass({
  render: function () {
    return (
      <a href={this.props.data.href}>{this.props.data.title}
        { this.props.data.hasOwnProperty('kids') ? <NodeTree tree={this.props.data.kids} /> : null }
      </a>
    );
  }
});
```

renders:

```
<ul>
  <li><a href="root/">Root Item</a>
    <ul>
      <a href="root/></a> <-- should not be here
      <li><a href="child1/">Child1</a></li>
      <li><a href="child2/">Child2</a></li>
      <li><a href="child3/">Child3</a></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>
```
